-- S&P GSCI Commodity Index Rises to 6-Month High; Metals Gain
-- B y   S t e p h e n   V o s s   a n d   J o h n   D e a n e
-- 2012-02-17T09:50:52Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-02-17/s-p-gsci-commodity-index-rises-to-6-month-high-metals-gain-1-.html
Commodities rose for a third day,
climbing to a six-month high, as metals and energy futures
advanced on improving U.S. economic data and optimism  Greece 
will get a bailout.  Americans last week filed the fewest claims for jobless
benefits since 2008, less than the most optimistic estimate of
45 economists surveyed by Bloomberg News.  The Standard & Poorâ€™s GSCI Spot  Index (SPGSCI)  of 24 raw materials
rose as much as 0.5 percent to 689.7, the highest intraday level
since Aug. 1. The gauge was up 0.2 percent at 687.95 at 9:37
a.m. in  London .  Industrial metals advanced the most, with nickel up 0.9
percent. Three-month copper climbed 0.6 percent to $8,345.25 a
metric ton on the London Metal Exchange while U.S. crude futures
rose 0.4 percent to $102.74 a barrel in electronic trading on
the  New York Mercantile Exchange .  Among the GSCI components, 18 commodities were rising and
six falling. Cocoa was the biggest decliner, down 1.5 percent.  To contact the reporters on this story:
